05456nam a22006495i 9780300127720DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001277207 a10.12987/97803001277202doi  a(DE-B1597)485481  a(OCoLC)1024025346  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aDS140.J475eb vol. 1 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320/.088/29604aThe Jewish Political Tradition :bVolume I: Authority /ced. by Michael Walzer, Menachem Lorberbaum, Yair Loberbaum, Noam J. Zohar. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (640 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tContents for Volumes I–IV -- tForeword -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Jewish Political Tradition -- tThe Selection, Translation, and Presentation of the Texts -- tLaw, Story, and Interpretation: Reading Rabbinic Texts -- tAbbreviations -- tThe Jewish Political Tradition Volume 1 Authority -- tIntroduction -- tONE Covenant God’s Law and the People’s Consent -- tTWO Revelation Torah and Reason -- tTHREE Kings -- tFOUR Priests -- tFIVE Prophets -- tSIX. Rabbis and Sages -- tSEVEN Controversy and Dissent -- tEIGHT The Good Men of the Town -- tNINE. The Gentile State -- tTEN. The State of Israel -- tGlossary of Names -- tGlossary of Names -- tCommentators -- tIndex of Biblical and Rabbinic Sources -- tIndex of Names -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book launches a landmark four-volume collaborative work exploring the political thought of the Jewish people from biblical times to the present. Each volume includes a selection of texts-from the Bible and Talmud, midrashic literature, legal responsa, treatises, and pamphlets-annotated for modern readers and accompanied by new commentaries written by eminent philosophers, lawyers, political theorists, and other scholars working in different fields of Jewish studies. These contributors join the arguments of the texts, agreeing or disagreeing, elaborating, refining, qualifying, and sometimes repudiating the political views of the original authors. The series brings the little-known and unexplored Jewish tradition of political thinking and writing into the light, showing where and how it resonates in the state of Israel, the chief diaspora settlements, and, more broadly, modern political experience.This first volume, Authority, addresses the basic question of who ought to rule the community: What claims to rule have been put forward from the time of the exodus from Egypt to the establishment of the state of Israel? How are such claims disputed and defended? What constitutes legitimate authority? The authors discuss the authority of God, then the claims of kings, priests, prophets, rabbis, lay leaders, gentile rulers (during the years of the exile), and the Israeli state. The volume concludes with several perspectives on the issue of whether a modern state can be both Jewish and democratic. Forthcoming volumes will address the themes of membership, community, and political vision.Among the contributors to this volume:Amy GutmannMoshe HalbertalDavid HartmanMoshe IdelSanford LevinsonSusan NeimanHilary PutnamJoseph RazMichael SandelAllan SilverYael Tamir  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aJews -- Politics and government. 0aJudaism and politics. 0aJudaism and state. 0aLeadership -- Religious aspects -- Judaism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aFishbane, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoberbaum, Yair, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLorberbaum, Menachem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo